data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` now throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

In .NET 10 you could configure `EnableSyncOverAsync()` as a temporary workaround — that API no longer exists in .NET 11.

## The fix

Convert every synchronous call to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods → `async` + `Await` the `*Async()` LINQ variants
- Rename methods with `Async` suffix (convention)
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

Note: `Add()` remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory. The actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
